"Cerda Lorca J., Valdivia C. G., Valenzuela B. M.T., Venegas L. J.","Climate change and infectious diseases. A novel epidemiological scenario [Cambio climático y enfermedades infecciosas. Un nuevo escenario epidemiológico]",2008,"Revista Chilena de Infectologia","25","6",,"447","452",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-59649099506&partnerID=40&md5=97ceafba6daa7162db39746325c1e90c","Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Facultad de Medicina, Departamento de Salud Pública, Chile; Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Programa de Especialidad en Salud Pública, Chile; Universidad de Los Andes, Facultad de Medicina, Departamento de Salud Pública Y Epidemiología, United States; Universidad de Chile, Facultad de Medicina, Programa de Doctorado en Salud Pública, Chile","Cerda Lorca, J., Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Programa de Especialidad en Salud Pública, Chile; Valdivia C., G., Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Facultad de Medicina, Departamento de Salud Pública, Chile; Valenzuela B., M.T., Universidad de Los Andes, Facultad de Medicina, Departamento de Salud Pública Y Epidemiología, United States; Venegas L., J., Universidad de Chile, Facultad de Medicina, Programa de Doctorado en Salud Pública, Chile","For the international scientific community, it is undoubted that planetary temperature is increasing, being projected an average raise of 1.0°C-3.5°C by the year 2100. Forecasted consequences are diverse, most of them adverse for human health, including the establishment of favorable epidemiological scenarios for the emergence and reemergence of infectious diseases. The present article summarizes the available evidence regarding the mechanisms that promote climate change, its environmental effects and its consequences on human health. In order to accomplish this objective, demonstrated changes in the dynamics of zoonotic, vectorial, food and water-borne diseases are described. The position of Chile in the international community is commented, as well as multiple pending challenges, among which outstands the importance of incorporating professionals that work in the health sector to the national debate.","Climate change; Global warming; Infectious diseases","Chile; climate; communicable disease; disease transmission; health; heat; human; risk assessment; short survey; Chile; Climate; Communicable Diseases; Hot Temperature; Humans; Risk Assessment; World Health",,,,,,"Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). Fourth Assessment Report (AR4). Summary for Policymakers. Disponible en http://www.ipch.ch (Accedido el 17 junio 2008)Greer, A., Ng, V., Fisman, D., Climate change and infectious diseases in North America; the road ahead (2008) Can Med Assoc J, 178, pp. 715-722; Haines, A., McMichael, A., Epstein, P., Environment and health: 2. global climate change and health (2000) Can Med Assoc J, 163, pp. 729-734; Khasnis, A., Nettleman, M., Global warming and infectious disease (2005) Arch Med Res, 36, pp. 689-696; Zell, R., Global climate change and the emergence/re-emergence of infectious diseases (2004) Int J Med Microbiol, 293 (SUPPL. 37), pp. 16-26; McMichael, A., Woodruff, R., Hales, S., Climate change and human health: Present and future risks (2006) Lancet, 367, pp. 859-869; Shea, K., Global climate change and children's health (2007) Pediatrics, 120, pp. 1359-1367; Barclay, E., Is climate change affecting dengue in the Americas? (2008) Lancet, 371, pp. 973-974; Senior, K., Climate change and infectious disease: A dangerous liaison? (2008) Lancet Infect Dis, 8, pp. 92-93; Rezza, G., Nicoletti, L., Angelini, R., Romi, R., Finarelli, A.C., Panning, M., Infection with chikungunya virus in Italy: An outbreak in a temperate region (2007) Lancet, 370, pp. 1840-1846; (2008) World Health Organization (WHO). Weekly Epidemiological Record, 83, pp. 105-108; World Health Organization (WHO). Climate change and human health-risks and responses. Summary. Disponible en http://www.who.int (Acce